                    overview: "Founded in 1824 (with its modern incarnation formed in 2004 by the merger of the Victoria University of Manchester and UMIST), the University of Manchester is the largest single-site university in the United Kingdom and a foundational member of the Russell Group. Located in the centre of Manchester on a sprawling urban campus along the Oxford Road corridor, the university hosts more than 44,000 students from over 170 countries — including approximately 14,500 international students. Manchester is the birthplace of the modern world in a uniquely literal sense: Ernest Rutherford split the atom here in 1917, the first programmable stored-program computer (the 'Manchester Baby') ran here in 1948, and graphene — the world's first two-dimensional material — was isolated by Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov in 2004, winning them the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2010. The university and its predecessor institutions count 25 Nobel laureates among their alumni and staff, including Niels Bohr, J.J. Thomson, and Alan Turing (who developed the foundations of artificial intelligence here in the early 1950s). Manchester is consistently the most-targeted university in the UK by leading graduate employers — the High Fliers report on the 2026 Graduate Market ranks it #1, ahead of Oxford, Cambridge and UCL. The university is also globally distinctive in sustainability — ranked 1st in the UK and 2nd in the world in the Times Higher Education Impact Rankings, and 9th globally in the QS Sustainability Rankings — with the UN Sustainable Development Goals embedded directly into core curricula across medicine, engineering and architecture.",
                    quickFacts: ["QS World Rank 2026: #35 Globally; #7 in the UK; #9 in QS Europe Rankings (third consecutive year in European top 10)", "Acceptance Rate: ~51% overall; ~10–14% for the most competitive programmes (Medicine, Computer Science with Industrial Experience, Aerospace)", "Founded: 1824 (modern merger 2004 between Victoria University of Manchester and UMIST)", "Total Students: ~44,000+ (the largest single-site university in the UK)", "International Students: ~14,500 from 170+ countries (approximately 22% of the student body)", "Nobel Laureates: 25 associated with the university — including the 2010 Physics Nobel for graphene (Geim & Novoselov)", "Most-Targeted UK University by Top 100 Graduate Employers (High Fliers 2026) — ahead of Oxford, Cambridge and UCL", "Times Higher Education Impact Rankings: #1 in the UK and #2 globally for delivery against the UN Sustainable Development Goals", "Top 5 in the UK across 14 subjects in the QS World Subject Rankings 2026 — including #5 globally for Development Studies and Architecture", "Birthplace of nuclear physics (Rutherford), the stored-program computer (the 'Baby', 1948) and graphene (2004) — three Nobel-winning scientific revolutions", "Member of the Russell Group; nicknamed 'the Original Red Brick' — the foundational civic research university model in Britain"],
                    financialReqs: "International undergraduate tuition for 2026/27 entry varies dramatically by faculty discipline: Humanities programmes are £24,000–£28,500 per year, Social Sciences £24,500–£29,000, Law £25,000–£30,000, Business and Economics £27,500–£33,000 (BSc Management is fixed at £33,100; BSc IT for Business Management £35,200), Science and Life Sciences £28,000–£33,500, Engineering and Physical Sciences £29,500–£35,000, Computing and Mathematics £30,000–£36,000, with MBChB Medicine sitting at £32,500–£36,000 for pre-clinical years and rising to £43,000–£49,000 for the clinical years. UK Home undergraduates pay £9,790 for 2026/27. Postgraduate taught international tuition runs £25,000–£35,000 for MSc Engineering, £28,000–£40,000 for MSc Computer & Data Science, £28,000–£38,000 for MSc Business / Management, and £23,000–£32,000 for MSc Life Sciences, with the Full-Time Alliance Manchester Business School MBA priced at £49,000 (total programme). Home PGT fees sit at the standard £14,700 cap. International PhD fees scale by lab intensity — £27,000 for non-laboratory projects, rising to £41,500 for highly equipment-intensive research. A defining institutional advantage is Manchester's regional living cost — £8,500 to £16,000 per year (£795–£1,642 per month), significantly cheaper than London-based peers and a major factor in the university's strong ROI for international students. The university may increase continuing fees by up to 7% per year for inflation. Major funding routes include the Global Futures Scholarships, Manchester Master's Bursary, Equity & Merit Scholarships (developing countries), Sir Bobby Charlton Scholarship, Chevening, Commonwealth, and the Manchester Alumni Bursary (£3,000 reduction for previous Manchester graduates).",
