                    heroImage: "https://images.pexels.com/photos/672532/pexels-photo-672532.jpeg",
                    overview: "Founded in 1829 by King George IV and the Duke of Wellington as a royal charter institution, King's College London (KCL) is the fourth-oldest university in England and a founding college of the University of London (1836). Located at the heart of central London with five campuses along the Strand, Waterloo, Guy's, St Thomas', and Denmark Hill, KCL sits at the geographical and cultural centre of the city — its Strand Campus overlooks the Thames opposite Somerset House, while Guy's Campus next to London Bridge houses one of the largest academic health science centres in Europe. KCL is best known globally for its medical, dental and health sciences heritage: it is home to the world's first nursing school (the Florence Nightingale Faculty of Nursing, founded 1860), the largest European institution for graduate and postgraduate medical training (the GKT School of Medical Education at Guy's, King's and St Thomas'), and the Institute of Psychiatry, Psychology & Neuroscience (IoPPN) which is the most cited psychiatry research institute in Europe. The university serves more than 42,000 students from 160+ countries and counts 14 Nobel laureates among its alumni and faculty, including Sir Peter Higgs (the Higgs boson, 2013 Physics Nobel), Maurice Wilkins (DNA structure, 1962), and Desmond Tutu. KCL is a founding member of the Russell Group and part of London's 'Golden Triangle' alongside Oxford, Cambridge, Imperial, UCL, and LSE.",
                    quickFacts: ["QS World Rank 2026: =#31 Globally (up from #40 in 2025); #7 in the UK; #7 in QS Europe University Rankings 2026", "Acceptance Rate: ~13% overall — among the most competitive in the UK; ~13–20% by course (Medicine and Dentistry into single digits for international applicants)", "Founded: 1829 by royal charter from King George IV and the Duke of Wellington — the fourth-oldest university in England", "Total Students: ~42,700 from 160+ nationalities (the 12th largest university in the UK by overall enrolment)", "International Students: ~40% of student body — one of the highest international proportions in the Russell Group", "Nobel Laureates: 14 associated with KCL — including Peter Higgs (Higgs Boson), Maurice Wilkins (DNA), Desmond Tutu, James Black", "Global Subject Standing: #2 globally in Nursing, #5 globally in Dentistry, #9 globally in Life Sciences & Medicine — 26 subjects ranked in the global top 50", "Home to the world's first nursing school (Florence Nightingale, 1860) and the GKT Medical School — Europe's largest postgraduate medical training institution", "Times Higher Education Graduate Employability Ranking: #6 in the United Kingdom — 90%+ of graduates in skilled employment within 15 months", "Five central London campuses — Strand, Waterloo, Guy's (London Bridge), St Thomas' (Westminster Bridge), and Denmark Hill — all within walking distance of Westminster, the City, and the West End", "Founding member of the Russell Group; member of the 'Golden Triangle' of elite UK research universities"],
                    financialReqs: "International undergraduate tuition for 2026/27 entry ranges from £27,100 to £40,450 per year depending on the programme, with Clinical Medicine and Dentistry rising to £61,000 per year. Standard programmes like BSc Business Management sit at £33,300–£34,990, BSc Economics & Management at £33,300, BSc Accounting & Finance and BSc Computer Science at £38,300–£40,450, BSc Psychology at £42,800, and Global Health & Social Medicine at £27,100–£33,300. UK Home undergraduates pay £9,790 for 2026/27 (a 2.71% increase from £9,535, with the cap projected to rise a further 2.68% to £10,050 for 2027/28). Postgraduate taught international tuition runs £25,000–£45,100 per year, with most MA / MSc programmes priced £32,100–£40,450, MSc Banking & Finance / Finance Analytics at £40,450–£45,100 (the upper tier), and the Executive MBA at £57,140 (total programme). Home PGT fees sit at £14,450–£18,150. International applicants pay a £2,000 tuition deposit on confirming an offer (£5,000 for Medicine and Dentistry, £6,000 for International Foundation Programme). KCL estimates living costs in central London at £14,400–£18,500 per year — total annual cost (tuition + living) is approximately £42,000–£60,000 for international UG. KCL provides extensive funding via the King's Living Bursary, King's International Scholarships, King's Indian Excellence Scholarships (£3,000–£10,000), the Felix Scholarship, Chevening, Commonwealth, Said Foundation, and Fulbright awards.",
